4 Assumptions for Multiple Regression Models

Exercise

Run a regression model called m1 predicting Variable1 from Variable2 and Variable3.


Refer to week 5 workshop for parametric assumptions. We will talk about some assumptions that are specific to linear regression models today.

4.1 Linearity and Homoscedasticity

Residual vs predicted plot is commonly used to examine linearity and homoscedasticity.

Two parts of this plot:

  • Linearity - a red line.
  • Homoscedasticity - black-white dots representing data points.
plot(m1, 1)

Interpreting R Plot

Assumptions are met when the red line is flat and horizontal (linearity) and the data points are equally and randomly spread (homoscedasticity).


Alternatively you can use the scale-location plot to examine homoscedasticity. It plots the square rooted standardized residual vs.predicted values.

plot(m1, 3)

Interpreting R Plot

Homoscedasticity Assumption is met when the data points are equally and randomly spread.

4.2 Normality of Residuals

Normality of Residuals can be examined by plotting the standardised residuals using a QQ plot.

plot(m1, 2)

Interpreting R Plot

Normality of Residuals Assumption is met when the data points observations fall along the diagonal straight line.

4.3 Multicollinearity

Several ways to check for multicollinearity, including:

  • Correlation Matrix
  • Variance Inflation Factors (VIF)

4.3.1 Correlation Matrix

We can use the cor() and corrplot() functions to create a plot of a correlation matrix.

corrplot(cor(d[, .(Variable1, Variable2, Variable3)]), method = "number")

Interpreting R Plot

Multicollinearity is indicated when the correlation between two (predictor) variables is below -0.9 or above +0.9.

4.3.2 Variance Inflation Factors

We can use the ols_vif_tol() function from the olsrr package to calculate the Tolerance and the Variance Inflation Factor values.

ols_vif_tol(m1)
##   Variables Tolerance VIF
## 1 Variable2    0.9999   1
## 2 Variable3    0.9999   1

Interpreting R Output

Multicollinearity may be indicated when VIF > 10.

4.4 Bivariate and Multivariate Outliers

We learnt how to inspect univariate outliers during week 5. For multiple regression, we also check for either bivariate or multivariate outliers.

  • For bivariate outliers, we can simply use the scatter plot.
  • For multivariate outliers, we can use Cooks distance.

4.4.1 Cooks distance

Chart of Cooks distance ols_plot_cooksd_chart() can be used to detect observations that strongly influence fitted values of the model. A data point having a large Cooks D indicates that the data point strongly influences the fitted values.

ols_plot_cooksd_chart(m1)

If we want a list of participants with outliers, we can use this code subset(ols_prep_outlier_obs(ols_prep_cdplot_data(model_name)), color == "outlier"). The obs column indicate the IDs of participants with outliers.

subset(ols_prep_outlier_obs(ols_prep_cdplot_data(m1)), color == "outlier")
##     obs      cd   color fct_color txt
## 10   10 0.01087 outlier   outlier  10
## 25   25 0.03496 outlier   outlier  25
## 71   71 0.02561 outlier   outlier  71
## 114 114 0.01241 outlier   outlier 114
## 120 120 0.01509 outlier   outlier 120

## 315 315 0.01917 outlier   outlier 315
## 316 316 0.01158 outlier   outlier 316
## 360 360 0.01245 outlier   outlier 360

As a rule of thumb, Cooks Distance over \(4/n\) (where n is sample size) is considered to be an outlier. We can also obtain this value using this code ols_prep_cdplot_data(model_name)$ts.

ols_prep_cdplot_data(m1)$ts
## [1] 0.01053

Interpreting R Output

Although the threshold for Cooks D for our data is 0.0105, it is mostly used to enhance graphical displays. We may consider a data point as outlier with values of D that are substantially larger than the rest. In this case, I would be inclined to remove ID 101, possibly 277 and 377 as outliers.


Tips

Always check for univariate and either bivarite or multivariate outliers for your multiple regression model.

4.5 Assumptions - Putting it all together

We can use the ols_plot_diagnostics() function from the olsrr package to obtain many relevant plots for checking assumptions. Plots that may be helpful include:

  • Residual vs Predicted Values - Linearity and Homoscedasticity
  • Normal Q-Q Plot & Residual Histogram - Normality of Residuals
  • Cooks D Chart - Multivariate Outliers
ols_plot_diagnostics(m1)


Tips

Assumptions checking for Multiple Regression:

  • Normality of Outcome Variable
  • Normality of Residuals
  • Linearity
  • Homoscedasticity
  • Univariate and Bivariate/Multivariate Outliers

5 Multiple Regression with Continuous and Categorical Predictors

5.1 Dummy Coding - Categorical/Factor variables

Factor variables in R are used to represent categorical data. Factors store data as integer values (i.e., levels) with a corresponding set of character values (i.e., labels) to use when the factor is displayed. While factors look like character vectors, they are actually integers. For example, when we make the sex variable a factor variable, by setting male = 0 and female = 1, sex variable will be displayed as male/female in R. However, when it is entered into a regression model, R will help us do dummy coding. Dummy coding is helpful as you can examine categorical variable in a regression model. Thats why we usually convert categorical data into factors.

Lets try this on the Sex variable. First, take a look at how it is currently coded using the table() function.

class(d$Sex)
## [1] "integer"
table(d$Sex)
## 
##   0   1 
##  93 287

We create a factor using the factor() function.

d[, Sex := factor(
  Sex,
  levels = c(0,1),
  labels = c("Male", "Female"))]

See how it is now after being recoded.

class(d$Sex)
## [1] "factor"
table(d$Sex)
## 
##   Male Female 
##     93    287

In the datset, we can see that the labels, rather than levels, are displayed.

# View(d)

You Try It

Convert the BornAUS variable into a factor. You can keep the name, or give it a new name.

5.2 Create Categorical Variables from Continuous Variables

As an example, I assigned marks to participants by creating a variable called Mark in the dataset d which has random values from 1 to 100. This variable is numeric data.

d[, Mark := rep(sample(0:100), length.out = nrow(d))]

We can create a new categorical variable called Grade that group these people according to their marks using the cut() function.

d[, Grade := cut(Mark,
                 breaks = c(-Inf, 49.99, 59.99, 69.99, 79.99, Inf),
                 labels = c("N", "P", "C", "D", "HD"))]
table(d$Grade)
## 
##   N   P   C   D  HD 
## 187  37  39  37  80

5.3 Changing the reference level of a factor

Factors in R come in two varieties: ordered (e.g., small, medium, large) and unordered (e.g., rose, daisy, lavender). For dummy variables, it is often helpful to set a reference level or baseline value. For example, consider our categorical predictor variable Sex with levels Male and Female. If Male is our reference, the model output for regression will give us a coefficient for Female, which can be interpreted as the difference in the outcome between Female and Male.

When there are more than two levels, this reference level becomes more useful for interpretation. For example, we may have a specific group that we want to compare against the other groups. Lets take a look at the Alcohol Risk Category variable in the PSY3062 dataset.

class(d$AUDITCat)
## [1] "character"

Since it is character variable, not a integer variable as Sex, we cant assign levels/labels to it. We will go head to convert it to a factor.

d$AUDITCat <- as.factor(d$AUDITCat)
str(d$AUDITCat)
##  Factor w/ 3 levels "Abstainer","At Risk",..: 3 3 3 3 3 3 2 1 3 3 ...

This works fine, but what if we want to compare all groups with the At risk group?

d[, AUDITCat := relevel(AUDITCat, ref = "At Risk")]
str(d$AUDITCat)
##  Factor w/ 3 levels "At Risk","Abstainer",..: 3 3 3 3 3 3 1 2 3 3 ...

5.4 Model

m2 <- lm(Variable1 ~ Variable2 + AUDITCat, data = d)
summary(m2)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = Variable1 ~ Variable2 + AUDITCat, data = d)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -23.923  -4.905   0.033   5.050  19.806 
## 
## Coefficients:
##                   Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)         21.767      3.478    6.26  1.1e-09 ***
## Variable2            0.409      0.176    2.32    0.021 *  
## AUDITCatAbstainer   -0.114      1.377   -0.08    0.934    
## AUDITCatModerate    -1.386      1.241   -1.12    0.265    
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 7.49 on 376 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.0207, Adjusted R-squared:  0.0129 
## F-statistic: 2.65 on 3 and 376 DF,  p-value: 0.0488

In the above output,

You can see that there is no row showing result for the At Risk group. This is because in the model, each dummy variable (Abstainer and Moderate, respectively) is compared with the reference group (At Risk). The coefficients tell us the difference in the outcome (Variable1) between the each group (dummy = 1) and the reference group (dummy = 0). These results are not significant, but if they are, we can write them up as below.

Sample Write-up for Dummy variables

A multiple regression model was used to examine whether Variable2 and Alcohol Risk predict Variable1. The results showed that, Abstainer had -0.11 lower Variable1 than the At Risk group [95% CI -2.82, 2.59], p = .934. The Moderate group also had lower Variable1 than the At Risk group (b = -1.39 [95% CI -3.83, 1.05], p = .265).

Notes. Results are not significant, this write-up is only for teaching purposes.
